<br>
Col Patrick Lang on Larry King has said that we should hold our ground and wait for a month until reinforcements arrive. He also said however, that this administration won't do that, that they will wait a couple days and then resume attacking the Guard piecemeal and it will cost us alot of our troops.<br>
<br>
Col Hackworth has stated that he has talked to his contacts (&quot;young officers&quot;) and that due to the lack of men, our troops are not getting rest because they don't have enough to fight in shifts.<br>
<br>
He also said the President authorized 8 divisions to go to Iraq, but Rumsfeld tried to go on the cheap and thus the reason we only have 4 divisions there. This was gambling with our troops lives to save money.<br>
<br>
Both men have criticized our leaders stubborn refusal to modify the battle plan to take into account guerilla warfare, something the CIA had told the pentagon would happen if we went in, but Rumsfeld (so they said) chose to ignore it.<br>
<br>
Now you can say these guys are retired and shouldn't speak to this war, but the number of former military, current military and military analysts that are speaking out on this  are more than just a spattering.<br>
<br>
We can still win this, but either things have to change on the Iraqi side for some reason or we have to start admitting that we need more troops and put a pause on this action till we get them.<br>
<br>
At least that's how I see it after 3 days of hearing the same things from different experts. I think a UK reporter said it best:<br>
<br>
There's two concurrent wars taking place - the real war in Iraq and the propaganda war in the US and UK.<br>
<br>
<br>
EDIT<br>
<br>
Edited first line to clearify it. Ritter is right under the conditions as they are today(which he may have been talking in reference to - I dunno), but the US could clearly win this with adequate troops and hardware... it's just we don't have those at present.<br>
