<br>
So the Iraqi government has however long for the 4th ID to get on line, to do more than harass the supply line.  All they have in southern Iraq are infantry, that can't form up into large forces.  If they form up into any sizable force that will allow them to cut off supplies, the allied air power will be able to eliminate the force.<br>
<br>
The Republican Guard is essentially stuck in Baghdad and the Northern city (forget the name).  They have tried to move out in force from Baghdad, I believe twice so far.  Each time, they have been cut apart by Allied air power.  If the Republican Guard turns and tries to engage US forces directly, like they tried a few days ago, they will get cut down completely, as they were.<br>
<br>
That is why the Iraqi government has been saying that they will welcome the US forces into Baghdad.  That is their best bet on inflicting heavy losses on the US/UK forces.  Problem with that plan is that it requires the US/UK forces to actually enter Baghdad.  I don't believe Bush will push to have that happen, because every day he has advisers telling him how many troops we will loose.<br>
<br>
So time is on our side, but not on Iraq's.<br>
<br>
So once the 4th ID comes on line, the supplies lines will most likely still be harassed, but not as nearly as much as it is now.  For each day, though the supply lines are being harassed, the Iraqis are being ground down.  They are loosing dozens, if not hundreds of troops in southern Iraq everyday.<br>
<br>
I don't know how many wounded we have, but its up in the hundreds (don't know what percentage of those have been taken out of the war), while we have only lost ~45 total among both forces.  The coalilition forces are still combat ready.<br>
<br>
So the question is. What will happen in that amount of time that could change the flow of this war?<br>
<br>
- Syria entering the conflict.  This would be a complex development.  Militarily, it wouldn't be much of a problem initially.  In order for them to be an actual threat, they will need to move a mass of troops to their border.  You best believe we will have our eyes locked on their troop movements.  If they do cross, I wonder what a few MOABs would do to a armor column.  I'm sure it would destroy their morale.  The real problem, is the propoganda war.  I'd be completely guessing as to its effects, but I realize that it would be bad.  This would open a huge can of whoop ass on the US/UK side, but Syria would have to sacrifice a portion of their troops.<br>
<br>
- Southern Iraqis.  Remember, they did rise against Saddam back in 1991.  The main reason why they are not doing so now is because how we treated that situation back then.  Given time, and enough convincing, they could rise up again against Saddam's troops.  Basra becoming a controlled city would help immensely in the propoganda war.<br>
<br>
- Saddam's Life Span - Without a doubt, you have to realize that there are informants inside Baghdad looking for signs of where Saddam is located.  There could even be special forces infiltrating Baghdad making attempts to get their gun sights on him.  Killing him in a way that it becomes known that he is dead will help bring about the uprisings we were hoping for from the beginning.  The more and more we see just tapes of Saddam sitting at a table with his homies, just leaves the question as to his status left hanging.  Now I haven't been keeping abreast of all the tapes that keep coming out, so I'm not sure how recently it has been determined that he was alive.  The longer the question of Saddam being alive or dead is left unanswered, the more likely those uprisings will occur.<br>
<br>
Really when you look at it, Iraq's options are extremely limited.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
There's two concurrent wars taking place - the real war in Iraq and the propaganda war in the US and UK.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You are very right.  We are currently winning the military war, without any doubt.  As for the propoganda war, I'd say we are winning out in the US and UK, as polls have indicated more support for the war.  We aren't winning there anywhere as much as we are in the military campaign. Now where we are loosing big, is in the Arab world.  I don't know about the rest of the world, but I wouldn't be surprised if we are loosing there as well. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6094" target="top">Wenin Huirunda</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
